{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17609388","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17609388"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:45:14+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:45:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16102"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16102","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16102"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.23,0,0.71,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8793"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72916"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8793","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8793"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16102"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58386"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1507"},{"type":"tags","id":"4090"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20991"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20995"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72916","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72916"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EVarious maternal factors can contribute to the risk of spontaneous miscarriage in early pregnancy. These factors may be mechanical, endocrine, immunological, or lifestyle-related.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes a mechanical maternal factor that contributes to the risk of spontaneous miscarriage?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Systemic lupus erythematosus","Cigarette smoking","Thyroid dysfunction","Fibroids","Diabetes mellitus"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFibroids\u003C/strong\u003E represent a mechanical factor that can increase miscarriage risk by distorting the uterine cavity, interfering with implantation, and potentially disrupting placental development. Particularly submucosal and intramural fibroids that impact the uterine cavity can affect pregnancy outcomes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other options represent non-mechanical risk factors:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESystemic lupus erythematosus\u003C/strong\u003E is an autoimmune condition that can cause miscarriage through immune-mediated mechanisms\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECigarette smoking\u003C/strong\u003E is a lifestyle factor that affects placental development and foetal growth\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThyroid dysfunction\u003C/strong\u003E represents an endocrine disorder that can impact early pregnancy development\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiabetes mellitus\u003C/strong\u003E is a metabolic condition that can affect embryonic development and implantation\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther mechanical factors that can increase miscarriage risk include uterine septum, cervical insufficiency, and uterine adhesions.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Uterine fibroids can increase the risk of miscarriage by distorting the uterine cavity and interfering with implantation and placentation.","Mechanical factors increasing miscarriage risk include structural abnormalities of the uterus that interfere with normal pregnancy development."],"references":["Lethaby A, Vollenhoven B. Fibroids (uterine myomatosis, leiomyomas). BMJ Clin Evid. 2015 Jun 2;2015:0814. PMID: 26032466; PMCID: PMC4451527.","Lee HJ, Norwitz ER, Shaw J. Contemporary management of fibroids in pregnancy. Rev Obstet Gynecol. 2010 Winter;3(1):20-7. PMID: 20508779; PMCID: PMC2876319.","T\u00eernovanu MC, Lozneanu L, T\u00eernovanu \u015eD, T\u00eernovanu VG, Onofriescu M, Ungureanu C, Toma BF, Cojocaru E. Uterine Fibroids and Pregnancy: A Review of the Challenges from a Romanian Tertiary Level Institution. Healthcare (Basel). 2022 May 6;10(5):855. doi: 10.3390/healthcare10050855. PMID: 35627994; PMCID: PMC9141014.","Arulkumaran, S., Ledger, W., Denny, L., \u0026 Doumouchtsis, S. (Eds.). (2019). Oxford Textbook of Obstetrics and Gynaecology. Oxford University Press.","Padubidri, V. G., \u0026 Daftary, S. N. (Eds.). (2014). Shaw\u0027s Textbook of Gynecology E-book. Elsevier health sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58386"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16102"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58386","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/58386"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-22T16:58:14+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-05T15:26:41+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8793"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72916"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"da